The "screws" are called set screws. They are designed so that they can
thread completely through the hub of the handle. They are normally driven
with an allen wrench and tighten by applying pressure onto the encircled
shaft.

Regarding the mill shaft - I sounds like the shaft has a flat cut into it so
that one of the set screws can lock into that area and prevent the handle
from turning on the shaft.

Thinking about what you have done so far - damage control is in order. I'd
suggest cutting the handle off by cutting slots parallel to the shaft 180
degrees from each other through the handle hub. I'd suggest using a Dremel
tool with a cut off wheel. It shouldn't take you but a few minutes. BTW -
wear safety glasses.
